y-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-introductory-tutorial/">Bodysuit with Corset Cups <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="24"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-measurement/">Party Dress <span>(17)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#544">Transparent corsets  <span>(4)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="25"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-cutting-a-mock-up/">Corset with Drapery <span>(20)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="26"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-and-the-throw-over-sewing-technique/">Corset with Integral Straps <span>(27)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="34"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model/">Corset with 3-Part Cups <span>(22)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="76"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-5/">Corset with a Fancy Cut-Out <span>(22)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#3082">Decoration Techniques  <span>(9)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="83"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials/">Rhinestones Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="84"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-glue-on-half-pearls/">Additional Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="85"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-thick-decoration-element/">Thick Decoration Elements <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="86"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials-2/">Wedding Dress Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="87"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong><em>Dressmaker’s Treasury&nbsp;</em></strong><strong>is a collection of key tools and skills which every dressmaker needs for successful work.</strong></p><p><strong>I am offering you a great instrument to help you acquire more confidence for fulfilling your creative projects!&nbsp;</strong>You will no longer have any fear of complex sophisticated garments! You will learn to work with mock-ups, make crinolines of non-standard shapes, and sew various kinds of fabric cases for petticoats to enhance the fullness of the main skirt.</p><p><strong>Our main goal at the Corset Academy&nbsp;</strong>is to teach you how to sew wedding and evening garments. And I want you to be able to sew a high-quality garment within a relatively short time.</p><p><strong>I don’t want you to spend lots of time on doing complicated calculations and making basic skirt patterns!</strong></p><p><strong>All necessary materials are included in the course:</strong></p><ul><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in the actual size (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in half the actual size for sewing mock-ups and designing new skirt models (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculation of all parameters required for cutting a trapeze-shaped skirt, a half-circle skirt, and a full-sweep skirt (HTML). These tables contain 18 tabs for calculating necessary parameters for the mentioned types of skirts, horizontal and vertical ruffles, falbalas, and the elastic waistband skirt.</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculations with fixed parameters for the trapeze-shaped skirt, the half-circle skirt, and the full-sweep skirt (HTML);</h4></li></ul><h4>Fixed parameters (i.e. measurements) allow you to quickly calculate necessary data for cutting ruffles and falbalas for a skirt of a certain size: consumption of main fabric, lining fabric, decorative materials, etc.</h4><p><strong>Our new course&nbsp;<em>Dressmaker’s Treasury. Wedding Skirts and Petticoats&nbsp;</em>is a collection of important methods and skills which every dressmaker must know in order to achieve good results. It will be equally helpful for beginners and for experienced professionals!</strong></p><p><strong>Every professional dressmaker knows that sewing complex wedding skirts&nbsp;</strong>is not just about sewing together kilometers of fabric. The key thing is correct calculations and your ability to “foresee” the final results and related fabric consumption well before you start cutting and sewing.</p><p>I would also like to emphasize that the skirt from this course is merely a foundation for your own masterpieces. Let your creativity bloom!</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Enjoy it!</strong></p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;6h 12m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-33-calculating-gores-for-cutting-a-petticoat-and-a-fabric-casing/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-33-calculating-gores-for-cutting-a-petticoat-and-a-fabric-casing/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2018-05-08T18:22:29+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2018-05-21T19:21:07+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2018"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 33. Calculating Gores for Cutting a Petticoat and a Fabric Casing."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 33. Calculating Gores for Cutting a Petticoat and a Fabric Casing."><meta itemprop="description" content="I have made these tables quite flexible: you can do all calculations for the petticoat, and for the face of the skirt based on your client’s measurements"><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding Skirts and Petticoats. Practical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding skirts and petticoats. practical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 33. Calculating Gores for Cutting a Petticoat and a Fabric Casing.</h1><p><strong>Included in this book along with the tutorials are several automatic calculation tables. </strong>I would like to make a short foreword before demonstrating you how to use them by certain examples.</p><p>It took me several months to develop these automatic calculation tables. I was using a large scope of statistical data and practical experience accumulated throughout decades of working with clients.</p><p><strong>Let me explain why you need these tables in the first place. </strong></p><p><strong>Here is the simplest example: </strong>suppose a client comes to your atelier, shows you a picture, and instantly asks “How much will this dress cost?”</p><p>It is great if she gives you some time to think it over, but you know it very well that she will be expecting an immediate answer. You see garment for the first time in your life, but there is no time to think. You need to answer immediately and give your rationale for the named price.</p><p><strong>What does the price consist of anyway? </strong>Normally, there are two key components: cost of materials and time invested in the making. But both these components have direct or indirect relation to fabric consumption.</p><p>You can more or less estimate the cost of materials and the cost of work related to the top part of the dress (a corset or a top, etc.) after a quick look at the picture, but the same things regarding the skirt will, in most cases, remain a question until you do certain calculations.</p><p><strong>And the skirt usually implies some serious calculations. </strong>A fancy wedding skirt is made of many separate parts. The petticoat, the fabric casing, the face of the skirt with all its elements, etc. It is sometimes hard to tell how the skirt was cut just from looking at a picture: is it a full circle, a half-circle, three quarters of a circle, or a trapeze? How am I supposed to cut this skirt? Should I divide it in gores or cut it as certain segments of a circle? And you start wondering about the petticoat as well: how to cut it if you need to sew it yourself? How long should the hoops be? What is the bottom circumference? And if you already have a ready-made petticoat with hoops, you will start wondering how to make a fabric casing for it, how many ruffles to put on it, and how much fabric it will take. And, of course, you need to decide whether the face of your skirt will feature flounces and ruffles, or whether it will be a plain elastic waist skirt.</p><p><strong>Just remember how many times you named the wrong price to your own disadvantage, mistaken about the expected fabric consumption and the pre-calculated number of work hours. But from now on, you will be able to determine fabric consumption for your skirt within an instant by putting the usual key parameters in the automatic calculation table. </strong></p><p>Imagine how impressed the client will be when she hears a well-reasoned price grounded on certain parameters and when you offer her to sit down together and choose the best option by playing with some variables, such as gathering ratio, degree of fullness, number of ruffles, etc. After getting it clear with fabric consumption and number of pattern pieces, you will easily calculate how much time it will take to cut the ruffles, finish them, and put them on the garment, make a fabric casing for the inner construction, and make all other parts of the garment. In other words, you will be able to choose the best possible dress with regard to your client’s budget and to your mutual benefit.</p><p><strong>So, what can you calculate using these tables? </strong>By putting the initial parameters in the table (they are Waist Circumference, Skirt Length, and Fabric Width), you will get an instant estimate of fabric consumption for any skirt (full circle, half-circle, with or without train, etc.), as well as a correct and fabric-efficient pattern layout. You will get all necessary radii for cutting your skirt, i.e. the waist opening and the bottom edge. The table will also suggest the best side seam length if your skirt features a train. Moreover, you will be offered complete calculations for dividing the skirt in gores if the width of your fabric or the style of the skirt suggests that you cut it as gores and not as circle-based pieces. You will be given the full hem length, which means you will know exactly how many meters of trimmings or other finishing materials you need to buy for the hem and, if applicable, for the train. If you have no idea how to cut a particular skirt (for example, a fabric casing for a particular petticoat) and all you know is the hem length, then you will be able to obtain all other necessary parameters by using the corresponding table. By putting the number of horizontal ruffles in the table, you will calculate the intervals between them and get the initial width of the fabric strip with seam allowances and the width of the finished ruffle. You can also determine total fabric consumption for the ruffles with regard to the gathering ratio and, if necessary, separate fabric consumption for the ruffles of the skirt and of the train. The table will also calculate the aggregate sewing edge length of all ruffles. This value can be useful when you want to replace the ruffles with some other decorative elements.</p><p><strong>In addition, </strong>the tables allow you to determine fabric consumption per certain number of ruffles, for example, for a fabric petticoat casing, even if the ruffles are not supposed to go along its full length. If the chosen style calls for vertical flounces or ruffles, the table will help you determine the intervals between them along the waistline and along the hem of the skirt, as well as the number and the length of the main long ruffles and the shorter ruffles for putting between them. You will be able to calculate the number of ruffles required for the skirt and related fabric consumption based on initial ruffle parameters. The tables also allow you to calculate the number and the lengths of petticoat hoops. There is a separate automatic calculation table for the elastic waist skirt. My tables can also be used for calculating skirts for little girls and mock-ups in any required scale. <strong>Calculated values help you estimate the general scope of work more precisely. </strong></p><p><strong>I have made these tables quite flexible: </strong>you can do all calculations for the petticoat, for its fabric casing, and for the face of the skirt based on your client’s measurements, or you can calculate different versions for separate parts of the skirt, such as ruffles or flounces put at different intervals or having different widths. There are nearly countless ways you can use my automatic calculation tables. See it for yourself by using them for all kinds of skirts. <strong>And now let us move to working with certain examples in practice.</strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2033.files/image041.jpg" alt="2018-04-30_23-05-51"></strong></p><p><strong>Put our client’s measurements and all necessary parameters of the petticoat in the tables (see the red arrows): </strong></p><p>- Waist Circumference – 80cm;</p><p>- Skirt Length – 100cm (in this particular case, it is the length of the hoop petticoat and not the length of the finished skirt);</p><p>- Hem Length – 270cm (in this particular case, it is the length of the bottom hoop of the petticoat);</p><p>- Waist Gathering Ratio – 1. This means there is no gathering below the waistline.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2033.files/image042.jpg" alt="2018-04-30_23-07-48"></p><p><strong>We get all necessary calculated data instantly (see the blue arrows).</strong></p><p>- Waist Opening Radius (R1) – 42cm;</p><p>- Bottom Edge Radius (R2) – 142cm;</p><p>- Sector Angle in Degrees (α) – 109 degrees;</p><p>- Hip Circumference max (HC max) – 114cm.</p><p><strong>HC max is a very important parameter which you must always keep under control: it must be greater than your client’s hip circumference. </strong>In other words, the calculated skirt will be too small for your client if her hip circumference exceeds 114cm. I will tell you what to do in this case in the end of the tutorial. And now let us suppose we fit in the specified parameters.</p><p><strong>An additional reminder pop ups whenever you put the mouse over the corresponding line of the table (i.e. “Hip Circumference max”). </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2033.files/image043.jpg" alt="2018-04-30_23-09-09"></strong></p><p><strong>You can basically cut a skirt like this as two pieces after drawing the calculated radii and marking down the found angle.</strong> Or you can divide the skirt in gores, but we will postpone it for later.</p><p><strong>You can view the cutting layout by putting the mouse over the word “Illustration.” </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2033.files/image045.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>And now let us calculate all parameters for cutting a matching fabric casing for our petticoat. </strong></p><p><strong>This is done in the section titled “Key Skirt Parameters for Desired Sector Angle.”</strong></p><p><strong>I copy the key parameters of the petticoat into the corresponding boxes (see the red arrows). </strong>Make sure to account for the fact that the casing must be longer than the petticoat. It may feature a train, and it must be a little looser in width.</p><p><strong>For this reason, </strong>suppose the front length of our fabric casing is 110cm and there is a small train at the back, which makes the back length 140cm. I put the desired sector angle in the table. It can’t be 109 degrees, as it was for the petticoat, because it must allow for a looser fit. Let us make it 120 degrees. The casing will be wider than the petticoat down the bottom.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2033.files/image047.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>The blue arrows are pointing at </strong>the resulting radii, side seam length, waistband parameters, total hem length, as well as separately calculated front hem length and back hem length necessary for cutting the gores.</p><p><strong>The fabric casing can also be cut as two pieces: the front and the back. </strong></p><p><strong>You can see a schematic layout by putting the mouse over “Illustration” (see the blue arrow in the picture below). </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2033.files/image049.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>It may make sense, however, to divide the fabric casing in several gores rather than just two pieces in order to spare some fabric and to make the cutting process easier.</strong> Let us see how it works.</p><p><strong>Go to the Gores tab of the table. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2033.files/image051.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Put all necessary data in the table, first for the petticoat and then for the casing, and select the desired number of gores. </strong></p><p><strong>The fewest number of gores is 4. </strong>This corresponds with a skirt made of one front piece with a fold line and two back pieces with a central back seam (or, alternatively, with a fold line).</p><p><strong>Let us select 4 as the desired number of gores. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2033.files/image053.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Look at the right part of the screen. </strong>There are small tables with data for cutting each separate gore. The more gores you select, the more boxes will be filled with calculated parameters.</p><p><strong>Now that we have chosen four gores, we can see suggested parameters for cutting two back gores and one front gore with a fold line in the middle. </strong>The back can be represented by two gores joined by the central back seam or by one gore with a fold line in the middle.</p><p><strong>The front gore with a fold line has the following parameters: </strong>right side (middle length) – 100cm, left side (side seam length) – 100cm, top – 20cm, and bottom – 68cm.</p><p><strong>The back gore with a fold line or either of the two back gores will have the same parameters: </strong>left side (middle length) – 100cm, right side (side seam length) – 100cm, top – 20cm, and bottom – 68cm.</p><p><strong>And now let us see what will happen if we divide the skirt in, for example, seven gores. </strong></p><p><strong>I select 7 as the desired number of gores. </strong></p><p><strong>Please note how the programme has divided the gores between the front and the back of the skirt. There are three front gores and four back gores (see the red arrows).</strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2033.files/image055.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>It is impossible to divide an odd number of gores in two equal numbers.</strong> The central front gore has a fold line in the middle, and it makes sense to make more gores at the back because it may feature a train.</p><p><strong>The central front gore with a fold line is two times narrower than the side front gore at the top and down the bottom as you can see from the table. </strong></p><p><strong>Let us look at the parameters of the first front gore. </strong>Its top edge is 13.3cm long, its bottom edge – 45cm long, and, since there is no train, its right and left sides are the same – 100cm long each.</p><p><strong>The second front gore </strong>is half as wide as the first one, but its right and left sides have the same length of 100cm.</p><p>The side back gore and the centre back gore have the same width at the top and down the bottom. But these widths are smaller than on the front gores because the front of the skirt is made of three gores, including one with a fold line, while the back is made of four full gores. In other words, the waist width is divided in three parts at the front and in four parts at the back. This explains the difference between the lengths of the top and the bottom edge of the front gores and the top and the bottom edge of the back gores.</p><p><strong>Let us see what we get if we select an even number of gores, for example, six or eight. </strong></p><p><strong>I select 6 as the desired number of gores. </strong></p><p><strong>The programme has divided the skirt into three front gores and three back gores. </strong>The central front gore with a fold line is two times narrower than the side front gores at the top and down the bottom.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2033.files/image057.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>All front and back gores will be absolutely identical if you select eight gores. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2033.files/image059.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>If you learn how to work with this table </strong>and keep an eye on your client’s hip circumference, you will have no problems calculating skirts with multiple gores or bell-shaped skirts of any desired hem length.</p><p><strong>By using this table, you will also find the answer as to how to correctly account for the waistline dip and the hemline dip on each gore in accordance with the radii of the skirt. </strong></p><p><strong>It follows from the table </strong>that there is a 0.3cm dip in the middle of the top edge and a 1cm dip in the middle of the bottom edge of each gore of our eight-gore skirt with a waist opening radius of 42cm (R1) and a bottom edge radius of 142cm (R2). And the more gores you make, the smaller this dip will be.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2033.files/image061.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Let us calculate gores for the fabric casing of our petticoat using the same table. </strong></p><p><strong>I enter all necessary parameters of the fabric casing: front length – 110cm, back length – 140cm (train included), and I select 5 as the desired number of gores. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2033.files/image063.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Now I can see calculated gore parameters in the right part of the table. </strong></p><p><strong>The fabric casing has a train, which affects the configuration of the back gores. </strong></p><p><strong>The first (central) back gore has the following parameters:</strong> top edge (half of the central gore) – 6.7cm, right edge – 136cm, bottom edge (half of the central gore) – 29cm, and left edge (middle) – 140cm.</p><p><strong>In its turn, the second (side) back gore has the following parameters: </strong>top edge – 13.3cm, right edge (side seam) – 131cm, bottom edge – 59cm, left edge (corresponding with the first central gore) – 136cm.</p><p><strong>Let us look at the depth of the dip: </strong>it is 0.8cm at the top and 3.2cm down the bottom.</p><p><strong>I highly recommend you should double-check everything very carefully before cutting the garment. </strong>Make sure all entered initial parameters were correct and remember to account for your client’s hip circumference. You might have to slightly adjust the bottom edge after joining the gores and carrying out a fitting.</p><p>All these things are normal because no automatic calculations can guarantee a perfectly shaped hemline.</p><p><strong>Please note that no gore lengths are supposed to include seam allowances. </strong>You are supposed to add seam allowances later and make them as wide or narrow as you normally do. As for me, I usually use 1.2cm seam allowances along vertical edges. But sometimes you want to keep a little extra width in case you need to let out some fabric, and then you make these seam allowances as wide as 2cm and make 3cm horizontal seam allowances so you can shape the top and the bottom properly.</p><p><strong>And now it is the time to talk about the situation when your client’s hip circumference exceeds the maximum suggested in the table. </strong></p><p><strong>We will start from the petticoat. Go back to the Skirt tab. </strong></p><p><strong>Let us, for example, use the following initial parameters: </strong></p><p>- Waist Circumference – 80cm;</p><p>- Skirt Length – 100cm;</p><p>- Hem Length – 200cm.</p><p><strong>The given hem length corresponds with the smallest possible petticoat. </strong></p><p><strong>Let us look at the calculated parameters. </strong>We can see that our client’s hip circumference is not supposed to exceed 102cm, which means she has to be quite thin.</p><p><strong>Suppose our client’s hip circumference is 112cm. </strong>It is obvious that she won’t fit in a skirt with a hip circumference of 102cm unless we adjust the pattern.</p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2033.files/image065.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Let us find suitable parameters to make the skirt fit our client in the hips. </strong></p><p><strong>We will do this by changing the waist gathering ratio until we get a suitable hip circumference. </strong></p><p><strong>The biggest possible hip circumference reaches 115cm starting from a waist gathering ratio of 1.2,</strong> which satisfies us entirely because our client’s hip circumference is even a little smaller: 112cm.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2033.files/image067.jpg" alt=""></p><p>But, at the same time, we can see that the waist edge has also jumped up to 96cm instead of the initial 80cm. We need to bring it back down to 80cm either by adjusting the waist gathering ratio or by making darts.</p><p><strong>And so we need to decide on the number of darts and on their widths. </strong></p><p><strong>I select the desired number of darts in the right part of the table. Let it be 6. As the result, each dart will have an opening with a width of 2.7cm. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2033.files/image069.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>What will happen to the gores? </strong></p><p><strong>Let us move to the Gores tab. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2033.files/image071.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I put all previously calculated parameters in the table (see the red arrows): </strong></p><p>- Waist Circumference – 80cm;</p><p>- Front Skirt Length – 100cm;</p><p>- Back Seam Length (no train) – 100cm;</p><p>- Calculated Sector Angle – 60 degrees;</p><p>- Chosen Waist Gathering Ratio – 1.2.</p><p>Suppose our skirt will be made of four gores.</p><p><strong>And now please look at the line titled “Narrowing at Waist.” We see 2cm there. </strong></p><p><strong>This means </strong>we need to remove 2cm from either side of the gore or, in other words, provide for 2cm darts in order to bring the waist circumference to our client’s measurement without gathering the waist.</p><p><strong>Please note that dart points are positioned on the hip line. </strong>That is about 18-20cm below the waistline.</p><p><strong>Put the mouse over the words “General Look of Gore.”</strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2033.files/image073.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>After narrowing each gore by the specified value, we will receive complete calculations for cutting the gores of our petticoat. </strong></p><p><strong>The fabric casing is calculated the same way. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2033.files/image075.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>We put initial and calculated parameters in the table: </strong></p><p>- Waist Circumference – 80cm;</p><p>- Front Skirt Length – 110cm;</p><p>- Back Skirt Length with train included – 140cm.</p><p>The waist gathering ratio (1.2) and the sector angle (60 degrees) remain unchanged.</p><p><strong>Let us divide the casing in six gores.</strong></p><p>There will be three gores at the front and another three at the back.</p><p><strong>In this case, </strong>there is a central gore with a fold line at the front and a central gore divided in half by a seam at the back.</p><p><strong>Please pay attention to the narrowing of these central gores: </strong></p><p>- The dart is only made from the princess seam side, i.e. from one side of the narrow central gore.</p><p>- There is no narrowing from the fold line side of the central front gore or from the central back seam side of the back gore.</p><p><strong>And here is another important detail. </strong></p><p><strong>When you start calculating a fabric casing for the petticoat using the table for calculating a half-circle skirt, make sure to compare the circumference of the casing with the lengths of the top petticoat hoops.</strong></p><p>The fabric casing of a ball-shaped petticoat is often cut as a half-circle skirt. But many people forget to double-check the size of this half-circle skirt at the level of the top petticoat hoops responsible for the ball shape.</p><p><strong>And it is very easy to double-check it! </strong>Just replace Front Skirt Length and Back Skirt Length with values equal to the distance from the waist of the petticoat down to the hoop you want to double-check without changing the initial parameters put in the calculation table. It is enough to check the circumferences of your half-circle skirt at the levels of the three top hoops.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2033.files/image076.jpg" alt="goldub-628"></p><p><strong>The table will help you figure out the circumferences of your half-circle fabric casing at the levels of these petticoat hoops and you will compare the resulting values with the lengths of the corresponding hoops of your petticoat. </strong>And if the hoop happens to be longer than corresponding part of the half-circle skirt, then you should find the difference between the two values and divide it between the number of gores and adjust their width at the corresponding level.</p><p><strong>In conclusion, I must confess there is no option for calculating fabric consumption in my table for calculating a skirt with gores. </strong>Unfortunately, I could not devise a universal formula since there are way too many possible options.</p><p>But it is very easy to calculate fabric consumption <strong>for each particular case </strong>as long as you know the sizes and configurations of all gores. You have already calculated all gores. You can draw them on a piece of squared paper, for example, at a scale of 1:10, cut them out, and arrange them on another piece of paper corresponding with the width of your fabric at the same scale of 1:10. It will be easy to calculate fabric consumption knowing the total length of the 1:10 layout.</p><p><strong>At any time thereafter, you will be able to cut a full-size garment very quickly by referring to the ready layout rendered by the table. </strong></p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation Tables of All Parameters Required:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sun/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/halfSun/index.htm" target="_blank">Half-Circle Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/dlina/index.htm" target="_blank">Full-Sweep Skirt</a> </strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation&nbsp;Tables with Fixed Parameters:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sunFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Shaped Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/halfSunFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Half-Circle Skirt</a></strong></p><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/dlinaFix/index.htm" target="_blank">Full-Sweep Skirt</a></strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Sewing patterns a